THIRTY-THIRD LEGISLATURE, 2026
STATE OF HAWAII
C.D. 1
A BILL FOR AN ACT
MAKING AN EMERGENCY APPROPRIATION TO THE DEPARTMENT OF HUMAN
SERVICES.
BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF HAWAII:
1 PART I
2 SECTION 1. This Act is recommended by the governor for
3 immediate passage in accordance with section 9 of article VII of
4 the Constitution of the State of Hawaii.
5 SECTION 2. The legislature finds that the federal
6 government shutdown that commenced on October 1, 2025, and ended
7 on November 12, 2025, threatened the food security of Hawaii
8 residents who receive supplemental nutrition assistance program
9 benefits, as well'as Hawaii's federal employees and contractors
10 whose employment and income were disrupted. The shutdown also
11 delayed access to other federal grant funding.
12 During the shutdown, the United States Department of
13 Agriculture, Food and Nutrition Service, issued multiple
14 instructions to the department of human services regarding the
15 benefit amounts and the timing of distribution for November
16 supplemental nutrition assistance program benefits. To fund
2026-3509 HB2310 CDl HMSO
iiiiiiiniiiiuiNiiiiiiiiiiii

Page 2
H.B. NO.
C.D. 1
1 these efforts, the department of human services redirected state
2 fiscal year 2025-2026 general fund appropriations from its
3 eighteen programs and received transferred funds from the
4 department of labor and industrial relations.
5 To date, the department of human services has distributed
6 Hawaii emergency food assistance program benefits to 81,399
7 eligible households, which includes 161,549 individuals enrolled
8 in the supplemental nutrition assistance program. To cover the
9 cost for 27,406 eligible households with a dependent child
10 totaling 101,655 individuals, the department of human services
11 can access federal funds from the temporary assistance for needy
12 families program.
13 The legislature further finds that the department of human
14 services needs an emergency appropriation in the amount of
15 $14,248,126 in general funds to cover the amounts it paid for
16 the response to federal shutdown, specifically: $11,807,126 for
17 the Hawaii emergency food assistance program, $2,000,000 to
18 support the Hawaii Food Bank for purchase and distribution of
19 food, and $441,000 to Aloha United Way for 211 call center
20 support.
2026-3509 HB2310 GDI HMSO
